postcontent: For auction is a Rare London Pistol Co. 31 cal. revolver. The information below is an excerpt from an article found on the internet. This example is in good condition except that the cylinder does not function correctly all of the time. It has a 3 digit serial number. "The mysterious London Pistol Company revolver was actually a product of the Manhattan Firearms Manufacturing Company. The London Pistol Company side-plated .31 caliber pocket pistol were factory-seconds possessing design flaws such as blemishes from screws driven completely through the right side frame or imperfect hand engraving. These weapons may have been placed in a sort of reject bin in various stages of completion. When Manhattan began to phase out production of the .31 caliber pocket pistols in favor of the newer .36 caliber Navy models, management decided to complete and market the factory-seconds under the London Pistol Company name. To these weapons were added the 1859 copyright date stamped beneath the pistol immediately in front of the trigger guard. Thus these were marketed most likely during 1860.Since these were factory-seconds, they had already been stamped with the Manhattan serial numbers. Consequently, no Manhattan pocket model .31 caliber pistols share the exact same serial numbers as those found on the London specimens. Waldo Nutter in his Manhattan Firearms believes less than a few hundred Londons were manufactured and sold. Our research has uncovered fewer than three dozen known specimens today (April 2008)The London Pistol Company revolvers are engraved with the company name only with no reference to a specific location of manufacture." I have a few more pictures that I will e-mail on request. Certified funds only for payment

I recently received a suspicious email in reply to a listing I have.  It went something like this...

Mark S: "to whom it may concern: I'm interested in your AK, can you ship? I'm in NY."

Me: "What exactly are you proposing?"

Mark S: " I never purchased anything firearms related from online or out of state before so I don't know the rules.  I'm interested in the AK would we need to go through a FFL holder or is this considered a private transaction?" 

Me: "Nice try... This must be a Fedral Agent. You know, as well as I do, selling firearms across state lines requires a FFL holder. Without an FFL the sale of a pistol across state lines is a FELONY! So, let me be crystal clear. I will not ship a firearm across state lines unless it is to a FFL. YOU HAD BETTER LEARN THE LAW BEFORE, YOU GO POKING AROUND ON THE INTERNET TRYING TO GET PEOPLE TO COMMIT FELONIES." 

You guys understand that we are living in strange times. Be aware that there are hostile parties looking to undermine Liberty in this Blessed Country. Don't get trapped.
